<DOC><DOCNO> AP880301-0196 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 2056EST</FILEID><FIRST>r p AM-Jackson 2ndLd-Writethru a0837 03-01 0456</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Jackson, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0837,450</SECOND><HEAD>Jackson Meets With South African Ambassador</HEAD><NOTE>EDs: SUBS penultimate graf to CORRECT to S.C., sted N.C.</NOTE><BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Jesse Jackson met with the South Africanambassador Tuesday and said he conveyed the ``outrage felt byfreedom-loving peoples everywhere'' at the recent clampdown ofanti-apartheid factions in that country.   The Democratic presidential candidate said he objected toPretoria's restriction of the activities of anti-apartheidorganizations and Monday's arrest of Anglican Archbishop DesmondTutu and other top religious leaders.   Jackson told a news conference later that the ambassador, PietG.J. Koornhof, asked for a follow-up meeting with Rep. RonaldDellums, D-Calif., who attended the meeting and who is sponsoringlegislation on sanctions against South Africa because of itsapartheid policy of racial separation.   The Democrat also called on the Reagan administration to takeseveral steps against the Pretoria regime.   He said he informed the South African ambassador of hisproposals, which include:   _ ``Comprehensive international economic and financial sanctionson apartheid.'' Jackson said U.S. corporations and banks should beordered to leave South Africa.   _ Invocation by the administration of a special session of theU.N. Security Council to seek international support for suchsanctions.   _ Broadcasting of news from South Africa via ``a new Radio FreeSouth Africa.''   _ Support for the so-called frontline states around South Africaand aid to build rail corridor railways so that Zimbabwe and Zambiawould not be dependent on South African trade routes.   Jackson said he attempted to telephone President Reagan on theeve of Reagan's Tuesday departure for a North Atlantic TreatyOrganization meeting in Brussels. Jackson said he spoke withnational security adviser Colin Powell and urged that Reagan seeksupport from the NATO allies for Jackson's South Africa proposals.   Jackson's press secretary, Elizabeth Coulton, said Powell agreedthe South Africa situation would be raised at the NATO meeting.   Campaigning earlier in Maryland, one of the Super Tuesday statesthat holds its primary next week, Jackson spoke to a downtownBaltimore rally and blasted Reagan for using ``government power totake from the poor and give to the rich.''   Of his recent second-place finish in the Maine caucuses, Jacksontold the crowd of a few hundred, ``There are signs we are growingevery day.''   He also walked through Baltimore's trendy Lexington Market foodbazaar shaking hands with the lunchtime crowds. He stood on a largeplant pot and shouted over the din, urging the crowd to vote forhim.   Later, Jackson flew to his hometown of Greenville, S.C., andproclaimed to a church full of people, ``It's good to be home.''   ``I'm a son of the South...I know the South and its ways,'' hesaid.</TEXT></DOC>